A 67-year-old male with chronic atrial fibrillation and type 2 diabetes mellitus presented with acute chest pain and diaphoresis. Electrocardiogram showed ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads. Troponin I was elevated at 6.8 ng/mL. He underwent emergent cardiac catheterization with percutaneous coronary intervention and drug-eluting stent placement to the left anterior descending artery. Post-procedure he was maintained on heparin drip, aspirin, ticagrelor, and metformin was held due to contrast exposure. Echocardiogram showed left ventricular ejection fraction of 35% with anterior wall hypokinesis.

