A 54-year-old female was referred for evaluation of a 4.2 cm thyroid nodule discovered incidentally on carotid ultrasound. Fine needle aspiration biopsy was performed under ultrasound guidance and cytology returned Bethesda category V, suspicious for papillary thyroid carcinoma. TSH was 1.2 mIU/L and free T4 was within normal limits. She underwent total thyroidectomy with central neck dissection. Surgical pathology confirmed papillary thyroid carcinoma, classical variant, 4.5 cm, with extrathyroidal extension and two of six lymph nodes positive for metastatic disease. She was staged pT3bN1aM0 and referred for radioactive iodine ablation therapy.

