A 3-year-old male was brought to the pediatric emergency department with three days of high fever up to 40.1°C, bilateral conjunctival injection without exudate, erythematous cracked lips, strawberry tongue, polymorphous rash on the trunk, and swelling of the hands and feet. Laboratory studies showed WBC 18,200 with left shift, CRP 14.2 mg/dL, ESR 82 mm/hr, albumin 2.6 g/dL, and elevated ALT at 68 U/L. Echocardiogram revealed mild dilation of the left main coronary artery with z-score of 2.8. He was diagnosed with Kawasaki disease and treated with intravenous immunoglobulin 2 g/kg and high-dose aspirin. Follow-up echocardiogram at two weeks showed interval improvement in coronary dimensions.

