A 78-year-old female with severe aortic stenosis, mean gradient of 48 mmHg, aortic valve area of 0.7 cm2, and symptomatic heart failure with NYHA class III dyspnea was evaluated by the structural heart team. She was deemed high surgical risk with STS score of 8.2%. She underwent transcatheter aortic valve replacement with a 23 mm balloon-expandable bioprosthetic valve via transfemoral approach. Intra-procedural transesophageal echocardiography confirmed good valve positioning with no paravalvular leak. Post-procedure she was monitored in the cardiac care unit and started on dual antiplatelet therapy with aspirin and clopidogrel. Permanent pacemaker implantation was required on post-operative day two for persistent complete heart block.

