A 71-year-old male with a long-standing history of ulcerative colitis underwent surveillance colonoscopy. Multiple sessile polyps were identified in the ascending and transverse colon. Biopsies from the ascending colon showed high-grade dysplasia with focal invasive adenocarcinoma arising in a background of chronic colitis. CT abdomen and pelvis showed colonic wall thickening without evidence of distant metastasis. He underwent laparoscopic total proctocolectomy with ileal pouch-anal anastomosis and diverting loop ileostomy. Final surgical pathology confirmed pT1N0 adenocarcinoma with clear margins and thirty-two lymph nodes negative for malignancy. He was referred to oncology for discussion of adjuvant therapy versus surveillance.

