A 34-year-old female at 30 weeks gestation presented with blood pressure of 162/108 mmHg on two readings six hours apart and 3+ proteinuria on urine dipstick. She reported worsening headache and visual disturbances with scotomata. Urine protein-to-creatinine ratio was 2.4 g/g. Labs showed AST 156 U/L, ALT 134 U/L, platelets 92,000, LDH 742 U/L, and uric acid 8.4 mg/dL. Peripheral smear showed schistocytes. She was diagnosed with preeclampsia with severe features and evolving HELLP syndrome. Magnesium sulfate was administered for seizure prophylaxis and betamethasone was given for fetal lung maturity. Continuous fetal heart rate monitoring showed category I tracing. Given worsening laboratory values, the decision was made for emergent cesarean delivery. A viable male infant was delivered with Apgar scores of 6 and 8.

