A 22-year-old male was brought to the trauma center following a high-speed motor vehicle collision. Primary survey revealed an unstable pelvis on compression, diminished breath sounds on the left, and abdominal distension. FAST examination showed free fluid in the left upper quadrant and pelvis. Chest X-ray confirmed left-sided hemopneumothorax and a left chest tube was placed with 800 mL bloody output. CT of the abdomen and pelvis demonstrated a grade IV splenic laceration with active extravasation, an unstable pelvic fracture involving bilateral sacral alar and left superior pubic ramus, and a left renal contusion. He was taken emergently for exploratory laparotomy with splenectomy and preperitoneal pelvic packing. Interventional radiology performed subsequent embolization of the left internal iliac artery. He received massive transfusion protocol with 12 units packed red blood cells, 10 units fresh frozen plasma, and 2 units platelets.

