A 59-year-old male with a 15-year history of Parkinson disease presented with worsening motor fluctuations, wearing-off phenomena between levodopa doses, and troublesome peak-dose dyskinesias. His current medications included carbidopa-levodopa 25/100 mg five times daily, entacapone, and pramipexole. Unified Parkinson's Disease Rating Scale motor score was 38 in the off state and 18 in the on state. Neuropsychological testing showed intact cognition with Montreal Cognitive Assessment score of 27. MRI brain showed no structural abnormalities. After multidisciplinary evaluation, he was deemed a candidate for deep brain stimulation. Bilateral subthalamic nucleus DBS electrodes were implanted under stereotactic guidance with microelectrode recording. Post-operative CT confirmed satisfactory lead placement. Programming was initiated at four weeks with gradual reduction in levodopa dosage.

